Base on the foregoing observations, we recommended and the BAC agreed to:

prepare and issue the Sixth Edition of the Philippine Bidding Documents in the future procurements of the Municipality;

provide the correct information for the projects in the bidding documents;

strictly adhere to prescribed period of action for the procurement activities;

scrutinize the documents submitted by the bidder and exercise diligence in the post-qualification process; and

strictly adhere with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and pertinent issuances of the GPPB.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:

require the Municipal Accountant to strictly and uniformly implement the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to require all officers and employees who are still in the service to settle/liquidate all their outstanding cash advances by sending demand letters;

in case of failure to settle/liquidate their cash advances, cause or order the withholding of the payment of their salaries as provided for under Section 9.3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 and impose the sanctions provided under the penal provision of Section 128 of PD No. 1445 and/or study the possibility of filing the appropriate charges to enforce settlement thereof in accordance with Section 9.3.3 of the same Circular and Article 217 and 218 of the Revised Penal Code; 

direct the concerned personnel to strictly require an Office Clearance from Money and Property accountabilities, pursuant to Sections 200 and 256, Vol. I of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual from all officials and employees who seek retirement, resignation, transfer or claim for death benefits in order that all accountabilities could be appropriately settled;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless prior cash advance given was first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, pursuant to Section 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002, and

require the Municipal Treasurer to report intact the collections and immediately prepare the Report of Collections and Deposits so that the Accounting Office could henceforth record the transactions.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the Inventory Committee to submit the inventory reports to the Audit Team in accordance with Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to fast track the reconciliation of the resulting balance of the physical count with the accounting records.  In the event that deficiencies/discrepancies exist between the Inventory Report and accounting records, the necessary adjustments/corrections should be made and should be supported with complete documentation;
instruct the Supply Officer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the required property and accounting records, respectively, to provide check and balance between the two separate but related records;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) recognize monthly depreciation expenses to properly reflect the correct carrying amount of the PPE; (ii) ensure that all PPE subject for depreciation have been provided with depreciation expenses; and (iii) prepare the appropriate adjusting entry to restore the cost and the related accumulated depreciation of the derecognized PPE prior to disposal; and
create a Disposal Committee who will take charge of the disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with the policies and procedures prescribed under Section 79 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and Section 502 of Government Accounting and Auditing Manual, Volume I to prevent further deterioration and realize additional income from sale thereof.

Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
MPDC to properly integrate the list of PPAs per LDRRMFIP in the AIP;
Municipal Accountant and MDRRMO to prepare and submit, respectively, the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM to the Audit Team in accordance with Item 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 and COA Circular No. 2014-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (ii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 for proper documentation of transactions; and (iii) Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 for proper recording of transactions;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) strictly adhere to the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 on the procurement of goods and services; (ii) furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Purchase Order/Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five (5) working days from the execution of the contract as required under Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009; and (iii) make sure that Purchase Orders contain basic data/information as prescribed by COA Circular No. 96-010 dated August 15, 1996; and
Municipal Budget Officer to reflect in the Certification on Appropriation, Funds and Obligation of Allotment (CAFOA) the specific LDRRM PPAs from which each disbursement was charged for proper evaluation of the amount expended per PPA.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:
secure authority from the local sanggunian for the implementation of projects, programs and activities with “generic terms” or in lumpsum amount;
direct the BAC to (i) comply with the period of action prescribed for each procurement process and ensure posting of Notice of Award within the prescribed period; (ii)properly conduct the post-qualification process, if necessary, conduct further investigation to validate the claims of the bidder; and (iii)properly evaluate the mode of procurement to be adopted; and (iv)ensure compliance with the requirements and procedures prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements;
instruct the implementing units/end-users to properly fill out the Purchase Request, Supplies Availability Inquiry and furnish the Accounting Office with necessary documents to support the disbursements made by their respective offices; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to (i)ensure proper recording of procurement and issuances of supplies; and (ii) secure necessary supporting documents before making payments.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Municipal Budget Officer to properly incorporate and identify the budget of GAD mandated PPAs in the Annual Investment Plan and Annual Budget in accordance with the budgeting per GAD Plan and Budget;
GAD Focal Person to (i) ensure that project proposal/brief of each PPAs in the GPB and the accomplished HGDG of attributed programs are attached to the GBP; and (ii) submit to the Audit Team the endorsed Annual GPB and GAD AR within the prescribed period under Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001;
Bids and Awards Committee to be guided by COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 in the submission of contract/purchase order and the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services;
Municipal Accountant to (i) see to it that supporting documents attached to disbursement vouchers are accurate and complete before processing claims pursuant to Section 474(b)(5) of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445; and (ii) record the transactions of the Municipality in accordance with the Chart of Accounts provided in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009; and
Municipal Budget Officer to reflect in the Certification on Appropriation, Funds and Obligation of Allotment (CAFOA) the specific GAD PPAs from which each disbursement was charged for proper evaluation of the amount expended per PPA.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the BAC to:
ensure the correctness of the information provided in the ITB;
conduct the post-qualification process properly, if necessary, conduct further investigation to validate the claims of the bidder;
comply with the period of action prescribed for each procurement process and ensure posting of Notice of Award within the prescribed period;
ensure compliance with the requirements and procedures prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements; and
see to it that POs are properly and completely filled out.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:

Local Development Council prepare the supplemental investment program for PPAs which are not included in the approved AIP;

Sangguniang Bayan ensure that ordinances are enacted for any realignment and augmentation of funds;


BAC comply with the issuances of the GPPB and provisions of R.A. No. 9184 particularly on the submission of documentary requirements as well as the posting requirements;



Municipal Accountant (i) submit the Driver’s Trip ticket and Report of fuel consumption; (ii) properly record donations received by the Municipality in accordance with COA Circular 2014-002; and (iii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the procurement, issuance and inventory of goods and property, plant and equipment procured by the Municipality including those acquired through donations either in cash or in-kind.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Head of offices to provide allocation (under LBP Form No. 4 of the Annual Budget) for each PPAs under their respective offices in order to check the correctness of the attributions for GAD PPAs;


GAD Focal Person to furnish the Audit Team with the results of the administration of HGDG and GAD Accomplishment Report for CY 2020;

BAC and its Secretariat to (i) consolidate the PPMPs of various implementing units and prepare the APP; and (ii) adopt the proper procurement in accordance with the procurement law; and

Heads of the implementing offices to: (i) ensure effective and efficient implementation of GAD-related PPAs so that benefits that could be derived therefrom will be enjoyed by the intended beneficiaries; and (ii) comply with existing accounting and auditing rules and regulations in the implementation of GAD activities.

